Even worse are the studies that say ‚Äúhaving a clear strategy around X is correlated with greater performance‚Äù. Managers that are successful typically have a clear strategy for their core business and that framework typically bleeds into anything these managers do, including X.
These types of studies fail to identify a causal relationship. For example, typically companies that are successful and growing rapidly will have more resources to make X an initiative.

The problem with a lot of research about the benefits of a business doing X is that they are not controlled experiments. Many studies survey companies doing X and measure it across companies and ‚Äúfind‚Äù greater profitability/revenue/valuation growth associated with doing X.

9. 
Cypher provides a mechanism other than an abstraction of "aliveness" via HP to give the players something to wager, something to risk. 
The interaction with Elbo doesn't inherently drift off into the nebulous realm of "RP."

8. 
RP between PCs and NPCs can be as free-flowing as one needs, but since Cypher characters have a finite resource in their Intellect Pools, interaction with this character becomes something to game through.

6. 
Since Cypher does not have HP (for players) and does not root its mechanical progression in sequences of combat and violence, this influences what the scene in the Midden Heaps will be.

4. 
Any system can technically provide this. But Cypher encourages this a bit more for the reasons listed above. 
Other systems "time" the characters based on a reduction of HP--a stat that only serves to be deducted through violence and harm.

2. 
It's from these that I speculate the "Narrative-first" approach really emerges through the experience.
Combat--conflict--is an essential part of a story--& when that is un-mechanized in the way Cypher encourages, we think of "encounters" as scenes, not "modes of play."
